<h2>Analysis, Critique and Suggested Modification</h2>
<h3>for the Proposed Improvements to Downtown Freeways and I-45 North</h3>

<div class="textblock"> <span class="italic" style="padding-right: 30px;">Page created May 10, 2015</span> </div>
<div class="textblock"> <span class="italic bold" style="padding-right: 30px;">Updated July 22, 2015, with TxDOT's response to the items of concern</span> </div>

<div class="textblock">Comments and feedback to <a href="mailto:houston@oscarmail.net">Houston@oscarmail.net</a></div>

<div class="textblock"><a href="http://www.ih45northandmore.com/">Official TxDOT Project Web Site</a>, Interstate 45 and Downtown</div>

@*<div class="textblock">
    TxDOT’s recommendation for downtown freeways and Interstate 45 North is the most influential recommendation for Houston’s freeways since the 1950s. 
TxDOT and its partners deserve credit for a bold plan to fully modernize downtown Houston freeways and enhance mobility.
However, review of the preliminary schematics reveals numerous points of concern which could compromise the ability of the new freeway system to meet current and future needs.
</div>*@

<div class="bold">Update, July 22, 2015</div>
<div class="updateItem">On July 20 I met with a TxDOT representative and representatives from HNTB, the consulting firm developing the design. HNTB provided a response to each issue in the list. A brief summary of the TxDOT/HNTB response is included with the item link below, and more details on the TxDOT/HNTB response are in the detailed item description.</div>
<div class="updateItem">HNTB developed the design with a VISSIM computer model using 2035 projected traffic counts supplied by HGAC. HNTB stated numerous times that the proposed design meets all performance objectives in the traffic model, including the points of concern in my list. However, HNTB did agree that many of my points of concern warranted further review, and the next version of the plan will include modifications, likely including improvements at some my points of concern.</div>
<div class="updateItem">For many of my concerns, HNTB says they are evaluating the issue. That probably means that are verifying that the model performance is valid.
     My interpretation and expection is that if the proposed design is demonstrating acceptable performance in the model, it is unlikely that cost-increasing changes will be made. And virtually all my suggested improvements increase cost. </div>

<div class="updateItem">I appreciate TxDOT's and HNTB's willingness to take a close look at each individual issue. Not all issues will be addressed to my satisfaction. But I'm glad that each item was reviewed and the design should ultiimately be the best it can be within the financial limits, political constraints and traffic model performance.</div>


@*<div class="textblock">
    Disclaimer:  
    The points of concern in this analysis are identified based on existing traffic patterns and bottlenecks, using a common-sense approach in terms of overall lanes and lane balance.
    TxDOT and its consultant (HNTB) almost use detailed projected traffic counts and computer modeling to develop the plan.
    The schematics used were downloaded from the project web site in April 2015.
</div>*@

@*<div class="textblock">
<div class="problem-solution">Comments on the removal of the Pierce Elevated</div>
    From the mobility perspective, it is undesirable to remove the Pierce Elevated. It is preferable to have multiple routes rather than a single route, and placing all traffic on the east downtown spine introduces a single point of failure for the entire system.
    Even with the realignment of I-45, the Pierce transportation corridor (sunken into a trench) could be valuable for managed lanes or to provide capacity for connecting traffic.
    <p>
    But the removal appears to be certain to remain in the plan and the removal should have benefits for new development, so I won't object and instead I'll focus on the concerns of the new plan, some of which are serious.
</p>
</div>*@

