<a name="59-montrose"></a>
<div class="problem-heading">US 59 Northbound at the Spur 527 split: insufficient lanes</div>
<div class="textblock">
    <div class="problem-solution">Problem</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Only six lanes at the split point, and (apparently) no lanes added further back near Graustark</li>
        <li>Slowed or stalled traffic on either direction will disrupt both connections</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="problem-solution">Potential Solution</div>
    <ul>
        <li>There needs to be seven northbound lanes through the trench approaching the downtown split, two for Spur 527 and five for the US 59 main lanes.</li>
        <li>The narrow section of the trench (Graustark to Montrose) needs to be widened. This is accomplished by using the high voltage right-of-way on the south side and removing the transmission towers. The power lines would be placed
            in an underground conduit.
        </li>
    </ul>


        <div class="itemStatus">July 2015 Preliminary Status: No changes expected</div>
    <div class="itemStatusText">HNTB says this area has acceptable performance in the traffic model. But I still have deep concerns. Northbound US 59 has six lanes from Shepherd to Mandel, where the two right lanes are merged into one lane to have five northbound  lanes.
In the proposed design, the five-lane section is retained for a short distance around Graustark, and then widened back to six lanes west of Montrose. That narrowing to five lanes for the short distance is of course a bottleneck. It makes sense to remove that bottleneck during this project, especially since the right-of-way is readily available from the high voltage strip south of the freeway. TxDOT says widening US 59  to have a consistent six lanes northbound is beyond the scope of the project
        and introduces more cost into an already-expensive plan. They also say that the five lane section could be widened in a separate future project.
    </div>

</div>

